\" (in Dutch), ''[[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]]''. Retrieved 28 February 2018.</ref>\n* '''[[Marjolein Faber]]''', [[parliamentary leader]]\n* [[Martin van Beek]]\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Dercksen]]\n* [[Peter van Dijk]]\n* [[Alexander van Hattem]]\n* [[Ton van Kesteren]]\n* [[Kees Kok]]\n* [[Dannij van der Sluijs]]\n* [[Gom van Strien]]\n\n===Members of the European Parliament===\n{{further|2019 European Parliament election in the Netherlands}}\n{{see also|List of Party for Freedom Members of the European Parliament}}\n{{see also|Party lists in the 2019 European Parliament election in the Netherlands#PVV (Party for Freedom)}}\nThe PVV lost all it seats in the 2019 European Parliament election. The party is however due to have an MEP appointed in the wake of the re-allocation of UK seats after Brexit<br />\n0 Seats:\n\n==See also==<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n{{Portal|Conservatism}}\n* [[Cultural conservatism]]\n* [[Criticism of Islam]]\n* [[Criticism of Islamism]]\n* [[Criticism of multiculturalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.pvv.nl/}} (in Dutch)\n{{Dutch Political Parties}}\n{{Geert Wilders}}\n{{Movement for a Europe of Nations and Freedom}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Party For Freedom}}\n[[Category:Party for Freedom| ]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Geert Wilders]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Political parties in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Anti-Islam political parties]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populist parties]]\n[[Category:Member parties of the Identity and Democracy Party]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the present-day Party for Freedom|the historic party|Freedom Party (Netherlands)}}\n{{short description|Dutch political party}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| colorcode = {{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}\n| name = Party for Freedom\n| native_name = Partij voor de Vrijheid\n| logo = [[File:PVV_political_logo.png|225px]]\n| leader1_title = Leader\n| leader1_name = [[Geert Wilders]]\n| leader2_title = [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House Leader]]\n| leader2_name = [[Geert Wilders]]\n| leader3_title = [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate Leader]]\n| leader3_name = [[Marjolein Faber]]\n| leader4_title = [[European Parliament|European Leader]]\n| leader4_name = [[Marcel de Graaff]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and years ago|2006|2|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/>\n| split = [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]]\n| headquarters = [[Binnenhof]], [[The Hague]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pvv.nl/contact.html|title=Contact|publisher=Party for Freedom|accessdate=7 May 2018|language=nl}}</ref>\n| membership = 1 (with parliamentary representatives)<ref name=\"parlementparty\">\"[https://www.parlement.com/id/vhnnmt7m4rqi/partij_voor_de_vrijheid_pvv Partij voor de Vrijheid (PVV)]\" (in Dutch), ''Parlement & Politiek''. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.volkskrant.nl/archief/favorita-en-de-duistere-financiering-van-partijen~a891355/ Favorita en de duistere financiering van partijen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[de Volkskrant]]'', 2008. Retrieved 20 February 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2010/11/24/ondemocratische-pvv-11973605-a1325361 Ondemocratische PVV]\" (in Dutch), ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 2010. Retrieved 20 February 2017.</ref>\n| ideology = {{nowrap|[[Nationalism|Dutch nationalism]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\">{{cite book |last=Pauwels |first=Teun |title=Populism in Western Europe: Comparing Belgium, Germany and The Netherlands |year=2014 |publisher=Routledge |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dmUtBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&hl=no&pg=PA117#v=onepage&q&f=false |pages=117\u2013118 |isbn=9781317653912}}</ref><ref name=\"europepolitique\">{{cite web |url=https://www.europe-politique.eu/wiki/Partij_voor_de_Vrijheid_(PVV) |title=Partij voor de Vrijheid (PVV) \u2014 Europe Politique |website=www.europe-politique.eu |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><br />[[National liberalism]]<ref>{{cite book |title=The Victorious Parties - Unity in Diversity? |work=The Extreme Right in Europe: Current Trends and Perspectives |first=Patrick |last=Moreau |page=106 |publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht}}</ref><br />[[Right-wing populism]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref name=\"Oudenampsen\">Merijn Oudenampsen (2013). \"[{{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=EUhMAQAAQBAJ |page=191}} Explaining the Swing to the Right: The Dutch Debate on the Rise of Right-Wing Populism]\". In Ruth Wodak, Majid KhosraviNik, Brigitte Mral. ''Right-Wing Populism in Europe: Politics and Discourse''. A&C Black. p. 191.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/netherlands.html |title=Netherlands |website=Parties and Elections in Europe |first=Wolfram |last=Nordsieck |year=2017 |accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref><br />[[Criticism of Islam|Anti-Islam]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Subramanian|first1=Samanth|title=Could the anti-Islam Party for Freedom come out on top in upcoming Netherlands election?|url=http://www.thenational.ae/world/europe/could-the-anti-islam-party-for-freedom-come-out-on-top-in-upcoming-netherlands-election |website=The National |accessdate=16 April 2017|date=9 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite book |first=Wayne C. |last=Thompson |year=2014 |title=Western Europe 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlgtBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&hl=no&pg=PA185#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |page=185 |isbn=9781475812305}}</ref>}}<br />[[Opposition to immigration|Anti-immigration]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref name=\"Thompson\"/><br />[[Euroscepticism]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n| position = [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tqlrRJHwjKoC&pg=PA239&dq=Party-for-Freedom+right-wing&hl=en&ei=NXk-TsL9LYqr-QaD-NWGBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBjgU#v=onepage&q=Party-for-Freedom%20right-wing&f=false|title=After the Nazi racial state: difference and democracy in Germany and Europe|author=Rita C-K Chin|publisher=University of Michigan Press|year=2009|ISBN=|page=239}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-38253122 Are Dutch voters really turning to populist Geert Wilders?]<br /></ref> to<br />[[Far-right politics|far-right]]<ref name=\"europepolitique\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trouw.nl/gs-b6725250|title='PVV is extreem-rechts'|first=Van onze|last=verslaggevers|date=10 December 2008|website=Trouw|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.rug.nl/research/portal/files/20875483/JB07LucardieDEF_1_.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/03/28/the-new-face-of-the-dutch-far-right-fvd-thierry-baudet-netherlands-pvv-geert-wilders/|title=The New Face of the Dutch Far-Right|first=Thijs|last=Kleinpaste|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/03/16/520376715/geert-wilders-dutch-donald-trump-takes-second-place-in-closely-watched-election|title=Geert Wilders, 'Dutch Donald Trump,' Takes Second Place In Closely Watched Election|website=NPR.org|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/mark-rutte-dutch-politics-eu-netherlands-european-union-brussels/|title=Mark Rutte\u2019s leaden touch|first=Tom-Jan|last=Meeus|date=22 October 2018|website=POLITICO|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/428866-far-right-former-dutch-lawmaker-who-said-the-quran-is-poison|title=Far-right former Dutch lawmaker who said the Quran is \u2018poison\u2019 converts to Islam|first=Owen|last=Daugherty|date=6 February 2019|website=TheHill|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n| international = \n| european = \n| europarl = [[Identity and Democracy]]\n| colours = {{Color box|#AE1C28|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#21468B|border=darkgray}} [[Red]], [[white]], [[blue]]<br />([[Flag of the Netherlands|Dutch tricolour]])\n| seats1_title = [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|20|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|5|75|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[States-Provincial]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|41|570|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|1|29|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[King's Commissioner]]s\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|0|12|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| website = {{URL|https://www.pvv.nl/}}\n| country = Netherlands\n}}\nThe '''Party for Freedom''' ({{lang-nl|Partij voor de Vrijheid}}, '''PVV''') is a [[Nationalism|nationalist]],<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/> [[Right-wing populism|right-wing populist]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/> [[list of political parties in the Netherlands|political party]] in the [[Netherlands]].\n\nFounded in 2006 as the successor to [[Geert Wilders]]' one-man faction in the [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]], it won nine seats in the [[2006 Dutch general election|2006 general election]] making it the fifth-largest party in parliament. In the [[2010 Dutch general election|2010 general election]] it won 24 seats, making it the third-largest party. At that time the PVV agreed to support the [[minority government]] led by [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands|Prime Minister]] [[Mark Rutte]] without having PVV ministers in the [[First Rutte cabinet|cabinet]]. However, the PVV withdrew its support in April 2012 due to differences over budget cuts at the Catshuis.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423035742/http://www.euronews.com/newswires/1490908-dutch-elections-loom-as-budget-talks-collapse/|archivedate=23 April 2012|title=Dutch elections loom as budget talks collapse|url=http://www.euronews.com/newswires/1490908-dutch-elections-loom-as-budget-talks-collapse/|publisher=[[Euronews]]|accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref> In the following [[2012 Dutch general election]] it won 15 seats, having lost 9 seats in the elections, still being the third-largest party. Following the elections, the party returned to the opposition and in the 2017 election, the Party for Freedom won 20 seats, making it the second-largest party in [[Dutch Parliament|Parliament]].\n\nIt came third in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the Netherlands|2014 European Parliament election]], winning four out of 26 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/652748-cda-5-zetels-d66-en-pvv-4.html|title=Meeste stemmen D66, CDA grootst|work=nos.nl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=25 May 2014 |title=CDA met vijf zetels grootste partij |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/special/cda-met-vijf-zetels-grootste-partij |website=RTL Nieuws |accessdate=26 May 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nThe PVV calls for items like [[administrative detention]] and a strong [[Cultural assimilation|assimilationist]] stance on the [[Integration law for immigrants to the Netherlands|integration]] of immigrants into Dutch society, differing from the established [[Centre-right politics|centre-right]] parties in the Netherlands (like the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]], VVD). The PVV has also proposed banning the [[Quran]] and shutting down all [[mosque]]s in the Netherlands.<ref name=politico/><ref name=voa/> In addition, the party is consistently [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Jos\u00e9 M. |last=Magone |title=Comparative European Politics: An Introduction |publisher=Routledge |year=2011 |page=17 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=g73UtvxJsFcC}}}}</ref><ref>{{citation |first1=Daniele |last1=Albertazzi |first2=Duncan |last2=McDonnell |title=Twenty-first century populism: The spectre of Western European democracy |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |year=2008 |page=164 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=tCGIAAAAMAAJ}}}}</ref> and since early July 2012, according to the platform it presented prior to elections in September, it strongly advocates withdrawal from the [[European Union|EU]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nos.nl/artikel/390859-pvv-nederland-moet-uit-eu.html |title=PVV: Nederland moet uit EU. (The Netherlands should get out of the EU) |publisher=Nos.nl |date=23 April 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nParty for Freedom is an association with Geert Wilders as its sole member; thus the party is ineligible for Dutch government funding, and relies on donations.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bolopion |first=Philippe |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/geert-wilders-far-right-party-suffers-donation-downturn/ |title=Geert Wilders' far-right party suffers donation downturn |publisher=Politico.eu |date=8 March 2017|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== 2004\u20132005 ===\nThe party's history began with Geert Wilders' departure from the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]] in September 2004. Wilders could not accept the VVD's positive stance towards [[Accession of Turkey to the European Union|Turkey's possible accession to the European Union]], and left the party disgruntled.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAlthough the VVD expected Wilders to return his parliamentary seat to the party, he refused, and continued to sit in parliament as a one-man party, ''Groep Wilders'' (Wilders Group).{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn June 2005, Wilders was one of the leaders in the campaign against the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe|European Constitution]], which was rejected by Dutch voters by 62%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutch say 'No' to EU constitution|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4601439.stm| work= BBC News |date=2 June 2005|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006\u20132010 ===\n[[File:Slotdebat verkiezingen (final debate elections) 2006.jpg|thumb|[[Geert Wilders]] (left) with other politicians at the final television debate before the [[2006 Dutch general election]]]]\n\nOn 22 February 2006, the Party for Freedom was registered with the Electoral Council.<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/>\n\n[[Bart Jan Spruyt]], director of the [[conservatism|conservative]] [[Edmund Burke Foundation]], joined Wilders in January 2006 in order to formulate a party programme and to train its prospective representatives for the forthcoming national election (then still scheduled for 2007).<ref>{{cite news|title=Spruyt sluit zich aan bij Geert Wilders|language=Dutch|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/1062338/Nieuws/Politiek/Spruyt-sluit-zich-aan-bij-Geert-Wilders.htm|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=4 January 2006|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\nSpruyt left the party in the summer of 2006 after it proved unable to build broad conservative backing, and people like [[Joost Eerdmans]] and [[Marco Pastors]] proved unwilling to join.<ref>{{cite news|title=Historische kans voorbij |language=Dutch |url=http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1271047 |newspaper=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]] |date=17 August 2006 |first=Addy |last=de Jong |accessdate=4 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526150442/http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1271047 |archivedate=26 May 2008 }}</ref> After the [[2006 Dutch general election|2006 elections]], Spruyt said he was not surprised that the Party for Freedom had gained seats but maintained that, if the Party for Freedom had sought cooperation with Eerdmans and Pastors, it would have won more, even enough to bring about a [[Christian Democratic Appeal|CDA]]-[[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]] [[2006 Dutch general election#Possible coalitions|majority]] government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spruyt: Negeren van Wilders onverstandig|language=Dutch|url=http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1282578/Spruyt%3A+Negeren+van+Wilders+onverstandig.html|newspaper=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]]|date=23 November 2006|first=Jacob|last=Hoekman|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\nLater, Spruyt commented that the PVV had a 'natural tendency' toward fascism.<ref>{{cite news|title=Weimar in aanbouw (deel 1)|language=Dutch|url=http://bartjanspruyt.blogspot.com/2007/01/weimar-in-aanbouw-deel-1.html|publisher=The weblog of Bart J. Spruyt|first=Bart|last=Spruyt|date=1 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> He later qualified the statement, though he didn't withdraw it. Former PVV candidate [[Lucas Hartong]] called Spruyt's claims 'a cheap insinuation'.<ref>{{cite news|title=Het is me wat!| url=http://www.hetvrijevolk.com/?pagina=2295&titel=Het_is_me_wat|first=Lucas|last=Hartong|date=2 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Het Vrije Volk]]}}</ref>\n\nIn an ''[[HP/De Tijd]]'' profile dated December 2006, the party was described as a [[cult]], with an extremely distrustful Wilders only accepting fellow candidates completely loyal to him, and compared the PVV to the [[Socialist Party (Netherlands)|Socialist Party]] led by [[Jan Marijnissen]] but without reaching that degree of organisational perfection.<ref name=HP2006>{{Cite journal|title=Haagse Sekte| language=Dutch| author=van der Horst, Alain |author2=Munk, Kirsten |author3=Niemoller, Joost|publisher=[[HP/De Tijd]]|date=1 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 January 2007, the PVV announced it would not field candidates at the forthcoming Provincial elections. This meant it would be unrepresented in the [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Partij Wilders doet niet mee aan Statenverkiezingen|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/article386300.ece/Partij_Wilders_doet_niet_mee_aan_Statenverkiezingen|publisher=[[Volkskrant]]|date=10 January 2007|language=Dutch|accessdate=4 April 2009|work=[[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau|ANP]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 January 2007, ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'' reported that a PVV intern had solicited for signatures on the website forums ''Dutch Disease Report'' and ''Polinco'', the latter a forum described as far-right by various organisations, among them the Dutch Complaints Bureau for Discrimination on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meldpunt.nl/dl/mdi-jaarverslag-2003.pdf|title=Meldpunt Discriminatie Internet|language=Dutch|publisher=Magenta Foundation|date=1 March 2004|accessdate=4 April 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20040808184259/http://www.meldpunt.nl/dl/mdi-jaarverslag-2003.pdf|archivedate=8 August 2004}}</ref> Any party participating in this election was required to collect at least 30 signatures from supporters in each of the 19 electoral districts; of the 1500 signatures the PVV received, the [[Antifaschistische Aktion|Dutch Antifascist]] group identified 34 known far-right supporters. In a response, Wilders said he regretted that far-right sympathisers had provided signatures, denied any personal responsibility for them and reasserted his dislike of far-right parties like [[National Front (France)|National Front]] of France and [[Vlaams Belang|Flemish Interest]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[NRC Handelsblad]]| language=Dutch| date=13 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|title=PVV riep steun van extreem-rechts in| url= http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/article598698.ece/PVV_riep_steun_van_extreem-rechts_in| first=Joep| last=Dohmen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Trouw]]|language=Dutch|date=13 January 2007| title=Wilders ontkent oproep tot steun extreem rechts|url=http://www.trouw.nl/laatstenieuws/laatstenieuws/article598962.ece/Wilders_ontkent_oproep_tot_steun_extreem_rechts}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[de Volkskrant]]| date=15 January 2007|title=Extreem-rechtse steun verdriet Wilders|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/article387621.ece/Extreem-rechtse_steun_verdriet_Wilders|accessdate=5 April 2009| language= Dutch}}</ref>\nNoted writer and columnist [[Leon de Winter]] later declared the affair to be the result of a campaign of [[demonization|demonisation]] against Geert Wilders led by ''NRC Handelsblad'' and ''[[de Volkskrant]]'' newspapers, as well as the broadcaster [[Omroepvereniging VARA|VARA]].<ref>{{Cite news| url= http://www.elsevier.nl/opinie/weblog/asp/artnr/134700/weblogid/4/index.html|title=De demonisering van Geert Wilders|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|date=15 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009| first=Leon| last=de Winter}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wilders.jpg|thumb|left|[[Geert Wilders]] in 2007]]\n\nFormer [[trade union]] leader and prominent [[Christian Democratic Appeal|Christian Democrat]] Doekle Terpstra proposed an initiative against Geert Wilders and the PVV on 30 November 2007, in the newspaper ''[[Trouw]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Doekle|last=Terpstra|title=\u2019Nee\u2019 tegen kwade boodschap Wilders| language=Dutch| url=http://www.trouw.nl/opinie/podium/article1518091.ece|newspaper=[[Trouw]]|date=30 November 2007| accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> Terpstra sees Wilders as promoting intolerance, and discrimination against Muslims. He is supported in his cause by the large Dutch trade unions and refugee organisations. Politicians and the public are divided on Terpstra's initiative.<ref name=\"radio\">{{cite news|title=Dutch show mixed reactions to anti-Muslim party |url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/071204-freedom-party-mc |publisher=[[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]] |date=4 December 2007 |accessdate=4 April 2009 |first=Hans |last=Andringa |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018231807/http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/071204-freedom-party-mc |archivedate=18 October 2008 }}</ref> The newspaper ''[[De Pers]]'' reported the next day that much of Terpstra's claimed support did not materialise.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tekort aan redelijke positivo's|url=http://www.depers.nl/binnenland/135616/Tekort-aan-redelijke-positivos.html|language=Dutch|publisher=[[De Pers]]|date=5 December 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|first=Kustaw|last=Bessems}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the Friends of the Party of Freedom commissioned a producer, who acted under the name of \"Scarlet Pimpernel Productions\", a pseudonym adopted out of fear of reprisal,<ref name=\"scarlet\">{{cite news|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/article524165.ece/Rapper_wil_25.000_euro_van_Wilders|title=Rapper wil 25.000 euro van Wilders|publisher=[[de Volkskrant]]|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=8 April 2008|work=[[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau]]|language=Dutch}}</ref> to produce ''[[Fitna (film)|Fitna]]'' ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0650\u062a\u0652\u0646\u064e\u0629\u064c}}), a [[short film]] by Geert Wilders. Approximately 17 minutes in length, it shows selected excerpts from [[Surah|Suras]] of the [[Quran|Qur'an]], interspersed with media clips and newspaper cuttings showing or describing acts of violence or hatred by Muslims. The film attempts to demonstrate that the Qur'an motivates its followers to hate all who violate Islamic teachings. Consequently, the film argues that Islam encourages acts of terrorism, [[antisemitism]], [[violence against women]] and homosexuals, and Islamic [[universalism]]. A large part of the film deals with [[Islam in the Netherlands|the influence of Islam on the Netherlands]]. The film's title, the Arabic word \"[[fitna (word)|fitna]]\", means  either \"disagreement and division among people\" or a \"test of faith in times of trial\".<ref name=\"hatred\">{{cite news|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=137624|title=Hold your breath: \u2018Fitna' spreading seeds of hatred|date=29 March 2008|accessdate=1 April 2008|work=[[Today's Zaman]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402234115/http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=137624|archivedate=2 April 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Wilders described the film as \"a call to shake off the creeping tyranny of [[Islamization|Islamisation]]\".<ref name=\"foxiranwarn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,324406,00.html|title=Iran Warns Netherlands Not to Air Controversial 'Anti-Muslim' Film|publisher=Fox News|first=Michael|last=Park|date=21 January 2008|accessdate=8 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nPolling by [[Maurice de Hond]] published in March 2009 indicated that the PVV was the most popular parliamentary party. The polls predicted that the party would take 21 per cent of the national vote, giving it 32 out of 150 seats in the Dutch parliament. If the polling results were to be replicated at a genuine election, Wilders would be a major power broker and could become Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/news/zijlijn/6235703/Geert-Wilders-Freedom-Party-rises-to-32-seats |title=Geert Wilders' Freedom Party rises to 32 seats |date=29 March 2009 |accessdate=29 March 2009 |publisher=[[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402002907/http://www.radionetherlands.nl/news/zijlijn/6235703/Geert-Wilders-Freedom-Party-rises-to-32-seats |archivedate=2 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/netherlands/4933687/Geert-Wilders-leads-Dutch-polls.html|title=Geert Wilders leads Dutch polls |first=Bruno|last=Waterfield|date=3 March 2009|accessdate=4 April 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nisnews.nl/public/030309_1.htm|title=Wilders Now a Celebrity in US and Prime Minister in Poll|publisher=NIS News Bulletin|date=3 March 2009|accessdate=4 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722014951/http://www.nisnews.nl/public/030309_1.htm|archivedate=22 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, De Hond's results were not uncontroversial, as they were based on a panel of people who have signed up for the election poll on the Internet and thus were not a [[random sample]]. According to Joop van Holsteyn, professor of election research, therefore, De Hond's polls were not [[Face validity|representative]] of the population.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrc.nl/opinie/article2168483.ece/De_peiling_van_Maurice_de_Hond_deugt_niet|title=De peiling van Maurice de Hond deugt niet; De waarde van een peiling staat of valt met een representatieve steekproef|newspaper=NRC Handelsblad|author=Joop van Holsteyn}}</ref> Other Dutch polls (Politieke Barometer and TNS NIPO) have shown contrasting results, with the PVV often getting less support, though still remaining very popular.\n\nOn 15 May 2009, the PVV asked Balkenende to support the foundation of a [[Greater Netherlands]] actively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvv.nl/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1975&Itemid=1|title=Partij Voor de Vrijheid|work=pvv.nl}}</ref>{{third-party-inline|date=January 2012}}\n\nBy February 2010, the PVV had once more become the most popular party, according to a poll by Maurice de Hond which said it would win 27\u201332 parliameary seats in the next election, up two from the previous poll in early January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angus-reid.com/polls/view/35028/dutch_party_for_freedom_recovers_top_rank/ |title=Dutch Party for Freedom Recovers Top Rank |publisher=Angus-reid.com |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://digitalehofstad.wordpress.com/2010/01/31/2e-kamerverkiezingen-2010-%E2%80%93-peilingen-31-01-2010-maurice-de-hond-pvv-de-grootste/ |title=2e Kamerverkiezingen 2010 \u2013 Peilingen 31.01.2010 Maurice de Hond PVV de Grootste |publisher=Digitalehofstad.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March 2010, elections for the local councils were held in the municipalities of the Netherlands. The PVV only contested these in [[The Hague]] and [[Almere]], because of a shortage of good candidates. MP Raymond de Roon headed the campaign in his home town of Almere. Fellow MP Sietse Fritsma was appointed head of the local election campaign in The Hague. Both men would continue to serve as MPs as well as local councillors after their election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2009/12/pvv_picks_second_mp_for_local.php |title=PVV picks second MP for local elections |publisher=Dutchnews.nl |date=21 December 2009 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> The PVV made big gains, suggesting that the party and Wilders might dominate the political scene in the run-up to the parliamentary elections scheduled on 9 June 2010. The PVV won in Almere and came second to the Labour Party in The Hague. In Almere, the PVV won 21 percent of the vote to Labour's 18 percent, preliminary results showed. In The Hague, the PVV had 8 seats \u2013 second to Labour with 10 seats. The local elections were the first test of public opinion since the collapse of the 4th Balkenende cabinet in February 2010. The municipal elections were overshadowed by the fall of the cabinet and the forthcoming parliamentary elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrc.nl/international/Features/article2497139.ece/Local_elections_overshadowed_by_national_politics |title=Local elections overshadowed by national politics |publisher=Nrc.nl |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2010, Wilders announced he would take a seat on The Hague city council, after it became clear that he had won 13,000 preference votes. Earlier he had said he would not do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2010/03/wilders_to_take_council_seat_i.php |title=Wilders to take council seat in the Hague |publisher=Dutchnews.nl |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/dutch-anti-Islam-MP-Wilders-wins-council-seat |title=Anti-Islam MP Geert Wilders has announced he will take up a seat on the local council of the city of The Hague |publisher=Rnw.nl |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> One week after these local elections, the PVV called for an inquiry into the elections in The Hague, since a YouTube clip allegedly showed irregularities, including more than one person entering polling booths at the same time and a voter not putting the ballot paper into the box. These calls were rejected. The Hague council said the municipal elections had gone well and that any complaint should anyway have been lodged immediately after the results were announced. In [[Rotterdam]], a full recount was held after a protest by [[Livable Rotterdam|Leefbaar Rotterdam]], a local party with a programme broadly similar to that of the PVV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/calls-local-poll-recount-hague |title=Calls for local poll recount in The Hague |publisher=Rnw.nl |date=10 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/rotterdam-investigate-proxy-voting |title=Rotterdam to investigate proxy voting |publisher=Rnw.nl |date=10 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2010, the PVV gave up trying to form a governing coalition in Almere. In a press release, the party said most of the other parties had refused to give ground to PVV demands on what it describes as ''\"essential issues\"''. These include what the party calls \u2018city commandos\u2019: street patrols to keep order in the face of inadequate proper law enforcement. Other obstacles were the PVV's demands for reduced taxes for Almere residents and its fight against what the party sees as ''\"the increasing influence of Islam in Dutch society\"''. The PVV complained that it was forced to stay in the opposition through the manoeuvring of the political elite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expatica.com/nl/news/dutch-rss-news/wilders-pvv-party-kept-in-almere-opposition_31769.html |title=Wilders' PVV party 'kept in Almere opposition' |publisher=Expatica.com |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010\u20132012 ===\n[[File:2010-presentatie-regeerakkoord2.jpg|thumb|[[Maxime Verhagen]] (left) and [[Mark Rutte]] (center) are presenting the coalition agreement with support of the PVV of [[Geert Wilders]] (right) in 2010]]\n[[File:Pvv.png|thumb|Distribution of the people that voted for the Party for Freedom in 2010]]\n\nIn the parliamentary elections of 9 June 2010, the PVV went from 9 to 24 seats (of 150), winning over 15% of the votes, making the PVV the third largest party in parliament.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nBy July 2010, the PVV again became the biggest party in the polls after the [[2010 Dutch general election|parliamentary elections]], following difficulties in forming a new coalition and the PVV technically being excluded from the coalition talks because the CDA showed reluctance to cooperate with the PVV. According to the polls, the PVV would get 35 seats in a new election, which is a record high number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nu.nl/politiek/2295043/pvv-historisch-hoog-in-peiling.html |title=PVV historisch hoog in peiling |publisher=www.nu.nl |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, during the difficult cabinet formation following the elections, the PVV emerged as a prominent player in a proposal for a new minority government in the Netherlands. While the party would not gain a ministerial appointment, the PVV would tolerate a centre-right minority government coalition: a proposed deal that would make the party one of the most influential forces. Led by [[Ivo Opstelten]], a former mayor of Rotterdam who was appointed mediator for the next stage of negotiations, the forming of a government of VVD and [[Christian Democratic Appeal]] (CDA) with support of the PVV was negotiated; the resulting coalition agreement \"included elements it pushed for, such as a [[Islamic dress in Europe#Netherlands|burqa ban]],\" though the ban was never put in place.<ref>{{cite news| title= Dutch government collapses after far right pulls plug| url= http://www.cnn.com/2012/04/23/world/europe/netherlands-politics/ |date= 23 April 2012| publisher= CNN| quote= The Party for Freedom did not get control of any government ministries, but the coalition agreement included elements it pushed for, such as a burqa ban. No ban has been put in place.| accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref>  The VVD and CDA would have to rely on the PVV to get important legislation through. With this deal the Netherlands would follow the \"Danish model\", since in Denmark the anti-immigration [[Danish People's Party]] also stayed out of government but supported a minority center-right [[Venstre (Denmark)|Liberal]]-[[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|Conservative]] government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castle |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/06/world/europe/06dutch.html |title=Outspoken Dutch Politician Makes Inroads |location=Netherlands |newspaper= The New York Times |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref> The very fact of the participation of the PVV in these coalition negotiations has caused fierce discussions in political circles{{which|date=December 2017}} and was considered{{by whom|date=December 2017}} very unlikely until recently.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAfter the elections, CDA parliamentary fraction president Maxime Verhagen first had stated that as a matter of principle he refused to negotiate with VVD and PVV about a centre-right government, saying that the PVV represented views that could not be reconciled with Dutch law. These objections on principle disappeared in five weeks and Verhagen turned out to be willing to negotiate over a cabinet whose fate would (also) lie in the hands of Wilders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trouw.nl/opinie/commentaar/article3153262.ece/Vooral_het_CDA_heeft_niets_te_zoeken_in_zo_rsquo_n__rsquo_bijzonder_rsquo__kabinet_.html |title=Vooral het CDA heeft niets te zoeken in zo\u2019n \u2019bijzonder\u2019 kabinet |publisher=Trouw.nl |language=Dutch| accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2012, [[Hero Brinkman]] quit the party, citing a lack of democratic structure within the PVV among other things; qualifying this with a statement of continued support for the minority [[First Rutte cabinet|Rutte cabinet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hero Brinkman quits the PVV, opposition call for new elections| url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2012/03/hero_brinkman_quits_the_pvv_op.php| publisher=DutchNews.nl|accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> Two days later, three members of the [[States of North Holland]] representing the PVV followed his example.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://article.wn.com/view/WNAT0cc025902c4813c68046c95b3a128b8b/| title= Drie Statenleden PVV Noord-Holland mee met Brinkman| language=Dutch|accessdate=8 April 2012| publisher= World News Network | work= wn.com}}</ref> In July 2012, [[Marcial Hernandez]] and [[Wim Kortenoeven]] quit the PVV, both citing what they considered to be Wilders' autocratic leadership of the party.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chesal|first=Robert|title=Wilders gives Dutch politics a roller-coaster ride|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/wilders-gives-dutch-politics-a-roller-coaster-ride|publisher=[[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]]|accessdate=16 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012\u20132017 ===\n[[File:Congresso federale straordinario - Torino, 15 dicembre 2013 29.JPG|thumb|[[Geert Wilders]] speaking at a [[Lega Nord]] event in 2013]]\n\nIn the [[2012 Dutch general election|parliamentary elections of 12 September 2012]], the PVV went from 24 to 15 seats (of 150), winning 10% of the vote.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn October 2013, the party expelled [[Louis Bontes]], but he kept his seat in parliament.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} In March 2014, [[Roland van Vliet]] and [[Joram van Klaveren]] left the party and also kept their seats in parliament.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn the [[2014 European Parliament election in the Netherlands|European Parliament election]] on 22 May 2014, the party kept its four seats in the [[European Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |date=26 May 2014 |title=Dit zijn de Nederlandse leden van het Europees parlement |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/special/dit-zijn-de-nederlandse-leden-van-het-europees-parlement |website=RTL Nieuws |accessdate=26 May 2014 |language=Dutch }}</ref> MEP [[Hans Jansen]] died on 5 May 2015 and was replaced by [[Auke Zijlstra]] on 1 September 2015.<ref>\"[https://www.parlement.com/id/vjvuh0bgrcmd/nieuws/auke_zijlstra_pvv_bevestigt_toetreding Auke Zijlstra (PVV) bevestigt toetreding tot Europees Parlement]\" (in Dutch), ''Parlement & Politiek'', 2015. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref>\n\nOn 16 June 2015, the Party for Freedom and other right-wing nationalist parties in the European Parliament formed the [[Political groups of the European Parliament|political group]] [[Europe of Nations and Freedom]].<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33147247 France's Le Pen announces far-right bloc of anti-EU MEPs]\", ''[[BBC News]]'', 2015. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref><ref name=\"foundationenf\">Eric Maurice, \"[https://euobserver.com/political/129140 Le Pen becomes group leader in EU parliament]\", ''[[EUobserver]]'', 2015. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref> [[Marcel de Graaff]] of the PVV and [[Marine Le Pen]] of the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] became the first co-presidents of this group.<ref name=\"foundationenf\"/>\n\n=== 2017\u2013present ===\n[[File:Geert Wilders tijdens een politieke campagne in Spijkenisse.jpg|thumb|[[Geert Wilders]] during the campaign of the [[2017 Dutch general election|2017 general election]]]]\n\nFor the [[2017 Dutch general election]], the Party for Freedom had an [[election platform]] of a single page.<ref>\"[http://pubnpp.eldoc.ub.rug.nl/FILES/root/verkiezingsprogramma/TK/pvv2017con/PVV2017-2021con.pdf Concept-verkiezingsprogramma PVV 2017-2021]\" (in Dutch), [[University of Groningen]]. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref> Before the election, all major parties said they would not form a government coalition with the PVV.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2017/01/vvd-leader-mark-rutte-says-zero-chance-of-coalition-with-geert-wilders|title=VVD leader Mark Rutte says 'zero' chance of coalition with Geert Wilders|publisher=DutchNews.nl|date=16 January 2017}}</ref> A typical House of Representatives has a large number of parties represented, since it takes as little as 0.67 percent of the vote to get a seat.  With such a fragmented vote, the PVV would have needed the support of other parties in order to make Wilders prime minister, even if it won the most seats in the House of Representatives. Wilders hinted that a \"revolution\" would occur if the PVV won the most seats and was still locked out of power.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/dutch-election-far-right-could-win-not-rule-country-known-liberal/|title=Dutch election: How the far Right could win but not rule in a country known for its liberal values|author1=Ashley Kirk|author2=Patrick Scott|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe party won 20 seats (of 150) according to the preliminary results, which is 5 seats more than in the previous [[2012 Dutch general election|election in 2012]] and made it the second-largest party in Parliament.<ref>\"[http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/27813134/__VVD_de_grootste__.html VVD de grootste, zwaar verlies PvdA]\" (in Dutch), ''[[De Telegraaf]]'', 2017. Retrieved 17 March 2017.</ref>\n\nThe party performed poorly in the [[2019 Dutch provincial elections]], losing 26 seats, with the [[Forum for Democracy]] taking many of its voters.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Politico]]|date=25 March 2019|title=5 things to know about Dutch far right\u2019s new figurehead|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/thierry-baudet-forum-for-democracy-netherlands-5-things-to-know-about-dutch-far-rights-new-figurehead/}}</ref>\n\n==Ideology==\n{{Updatesection|date=October 2016}}\nThe Party for Freedom combines conservative, liberal, right and left standpoints in a populistic programme.<ref name=\"www.parlement.com\">[http://www.parlement.com/9291000/modulesf/g45eq8f7 Partijen in de Eerste en Tweede Kamer - PVV], Parlement.com.</ref> On certain themes like healthcare, social services and elderly care the PVV can be seen as left and social, though selective.<ref>[https://nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/03/12/de-pvv-is-best-sociaal-maar-wel-selectief-7328509-a1549996 De PVV is best sociaal, maar wel selectief], ''NRC Handelsblad'', 12 maart 2017 (ism. Parlementair Documentatiecentrum)</ref> Regarding immigration and culture the party is nationalistic. It believes that the [[Judeo-Christian]] and [[humanism|humanist]] traditions should be taken as the dominant culture in the Netherlands, and that immigrants should adapt accordingly. The party wants a halt to immigration especially from non-Western countries. It is hostile towards the EU, is against future [[Enlargement of the European Union|EU enlargement]] to Muslim-majority countries like Turkey and opposes a dominant presence of Islam in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvv-europa.nl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4&Itemid=2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410003337/http://pvv-europa.nl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4&Itemid=2|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 April 2009|title=Standpunten|language=Dutch|work=Voor Nederland in Europa|publisher=Party for Freedom|date=1 April 2009|accessdate=7 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> More specifically, the party has called for a banning the [[Quran]], and shutting down all mosques in the Netherlands.<ref name=politico>{{cite news|title=Dutch party wants to outlaw mosques, Islamic schools, Koran|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/far-right-dutch-politician-backs-mosques-koran-ban-islamic-schools/|publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref><ref name=voa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/europe/dutch-far-right-leader-seeks-ban-quran-mosques|title=Dutch Far-right Leader Seeks Ban on Quran, Mosques|website=Voice of America|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/netherlands-pvv-leader-geert-wilders-koran-islam-mosque-ban-holland-dutch-pm-favourite-a7214356.html|title=The Netherlands' most popular party wants to ban all mosques|date=28 August 2016|website=The Independent|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref> The party is also opposed to [[dual citizenship]] (see below).\n\nThe Parliamentary Documentation Center (Parlementair Documentatie Centrum) of the [[Leiden University]] characterises the PVV as \"[[populism|populist]], with both [[conservatism|conservative]], [[liberalism|liberal]], [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] and [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] positions\".<ref name=\"parlement.com\">[http://www.parlement.com/9291000/modulesf/g45eq8f7 Partijen in de Eerste en Tweede Kamer - PVV], Parlement.com</ref>\n\n[[File:Pol-landschap-2012.png|thumb|On [[Andr\u00e9 Krouwel]]'s map of the Dutch political spectrum in 2012, the Party for Freedom is [[Conservatism|conservative]] on the socio-cultural axis, and [[Centrism|centrist]] on the socio-economic axis.]]\nIn December 2008, the eighth study \"Monitor Racism and Extremism\",<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.annefrank.org/upload/Downloads/Monitor2008-8.pdf |first1=Jaap |last1=Van Donselaar |first2=Peter R. |last2=Rodrigues |title=Monitor Racisme & Extremisme |publisher=Pallas Publications |year=2008 |language=Dutch}}</ref> conducted by the [[Anne Frank Foundation]] and the [[Leiden University]], has found that the Party for Freedom can be considered [[Far-right politics|extreme right-wing]], although \"with ifs and buts\". Economically they are viewed as a left-wing party. Peter Rodrigues and Jaap van Donselaar, who have academically guided the study, explain this classification with the [[Islamophobia]], [[nationalism]], and \"sharp aversion to the strange\", subsumed as [[racism]], which they have observed within the party.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nieuws.leidenuniv.nl/nieuwsarchief/monitor-racisme-en-extremisme.html |title=Monitor Racisme en Extremisme |publisher=University of Leiden |date=10 December 2008 |language=Dutch |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nu.nl/algemeen/1880292/pvv-volgens-onderzoekers-extreemrechts.html |title=PVV volgens onderzoekers extreemrechts |publisher=NU.nl |date=10 December 2008|language=Dutch |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, the report ''Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland''<ref>{{Citation |last=Moors |first=Hans|title=Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland. Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009 |publisher=IVA beleidsonderzoek en advies |year=2009 |language=Dutch |url=http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/bestanden/documenten-en-publicaties/kamerstukken/2010/01/27/polarisatie-en-radicalisering-in-nederland-een-verkenning-van-de-stand-van-zaken-in-2009/verkenningpr-definitieveversie16-12.pdf|display-authors=etal}}</ref> (transl. \"Polarisation and radicalisation in the Netherlands\") by political researchers Moors, Lenke Balogh, Van Donselaar and De Graaff from the [[Tilburg University]] research group IVA<ref name=\"IVA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lokaalcentraal.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Polarisering-radicalisering-in-NL.pdf |first1=Hans |last1=Moors |first2=Lenke |last2=Balogh |first3=Jaap |last3=van Donselaar |first4=Bob |last4=de Graaff |title=Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland: Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009 |publisher=IVA |year=2009 |accessdate=6 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316195636/http://www.lokaalcentraal.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Polarisering-radicalisering-in-NL.pdf |archivedate=16 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> stated that the PVV was not an extreme right-wing party, but contained some radical right-wing elements. The study claims that the PVV holds [[Xenophobia|xenophobic]] ideas, but not antisemitic ideas \u2013 the PVV describes its culture as [[Judeo-Christian|Jewish-Christian]] humanistic.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Hans Moors|author2=Lenke Balogh|author3=Jaap van Donselaar|author4=Bob de Graaff|title=Polarisatie en radicalising in Nederland. Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009|year=2009|location=Tilburg|url=http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|format=PDF|language=Dutch|page=15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154546/http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \"The PVV statements on [[Islamization|Islamisation]] and non-Western immigrants appear to be discriminatory and the party organisation is authoritarian rather than democratic\", said the researchers, who were looking into polarisation and radicalism across the Netherlands. They described the PVV as the \"new radical right\", a party with a national democratic ideology but without extreme right-wing roots. In particular, the report stated that the party's pro-Israel stance showed that it was not [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]]. It tends however towards a national democratic ideology. Wilders called the report \"scandalous\"\u2014in particular the link between defending the national interest and the radical right.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAn alleged earlier version of the report, leaked to the Dutch daily newspaper ''[[de Volkskrant]]'' in November 2009, said that Wilders' party is an extreme right-wing grouping and a threat to social cohesion and democracy. The paper claimed at the time the researchers were under pressure to water down the conclusions because of their political sensitivity.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} The Dutch [[Ministry of the Interior and Kingdom Relations|Minister of the Interior and Kingdom Relations]] [[Guusje ter Horst]], (2007\u20132010), [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour (PvdA)]], who commissioned the research, denied exerting any interference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2010/01/wilders_party_is_new_radical_r.php |title=Wilders' party is 'new radical right' |publisher=Dutchnews.nl |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/putting-geert-wilders-political-map |title=Putting Geert Wilders on the political map |publisher=Rnw.nl |accessdate=18 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529054622/http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/putting-geert-wilders-political-map |archivedate=29 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In response, Wilders accused her of \"playing a dirty game\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://extra.volkskrant.nl/opinie/artikel/show/id/5059/WC-eend_adviseert_Guusje_ter_Horst |title=WC-eend adviseert Guusje ter Horst |publisher=Extra.volkskrant.nl |accessdate=18 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100202133613/http://extra.volkskrant.nl/opinie/artikel/show/id/5059/WC-eend_adviseert_Guusje_ter_Horst |archivedate=2 February 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/Nieuws/Politiek/257065/Wilders-Minister-Ter-Horst-speelt-vuil-spelletje.htm |title=Wilders: Minister Ter Horst speelt vuil spelletje |publisher=Elsevier.nl |date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152439/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/Nieuws/Politiek/257065/Wilders-Minister-Ter-Horst-speelt-vuil-spelletje.htm |archivedate=24 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSome commentators and international scholarly publications have argued that the party is far-right; for example, the ex-prime minister [[Dries van Agt|Van Agt]] regards the party as ultra-right-wing, and [[Bert de Vries]] (CDA) draws comparisons with the small [[Centre Party (Netherlands)|Centre Party]].<ref>{{Citation|author1=Hans Moors|author2=Lenke Balogh|author3=Jaap van Donselaar|author4=Bob de Graaff|title=Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland. Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009|year=2009|location=Tilburg|url=http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|format=PDF|language=Dutch|page=96|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154546/http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The political scientist Lucardie, on the other hand, considers it necessary to reserve the 'far-right' qualification for [[Nazism|national socialists]] and fascists, though PVV is itself widely accused of fascism.<ref>A. Lucardie, \u2018Rechtsextremisme, populisme of democratisch patriotisme? Opmerkingen over de politieke plaatsbepaling van de Partij voor de Vrijheid en Trots op Nederland\u2019, in: G. Voerman (ed.), Jaarboek 2007, Groningen z.j.</ref> International media outlets, similarly, have followed this classification.<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=uWX_7eIGEHkC |page=142 }} |title=The governance of Britain: review of voting systems, the experience of new voting systems in the United Kingdom since 1997|author=Ministry of Justice|publisher=The Stationery Office|year=2008|ISBN=0-10-173042-X|page=142}}<br />{{cite book|author=David Marquand|title=The End of the West: The Once and Future Europe|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2011|ISBN=0-691-14159-2|page=51 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=XuhL44T-X8MC |page=51 }} }}<br />{{Citation |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=fM27iN7438kC}} |first=Johannes |last=Lindvall |title=Mass Unemployment and the State |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |page=118}}<br />{{Citation |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=9dUTXJakqLoC |page=187 }} |first=David |last=Art |title=Inside the Radical Right |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2011 |page=187}}<br />{{Citation |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=8kB6gvNZtNgC |page=106 }} |first1=Thierry |last1=Chopin |first2=Michel |last2=Foucher |title=Schuman Report on Europe: State of the Union 2011 |publisher=Springer |year=2011 |page=106}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2010/0602/1224271677559.html |title=Dutch liberal leader topping polls ahead of next week's election \u2013 The Irish Times \u2013 Wed, 2 June 2010 |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=2 June 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}<br />{{cite news|author=Peter Beaumont, Almere |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/may/16/geert-wilders-pvv-holland-netherlands |title=Geert Wilders, the ultra-right firebrand, campaigns to be Holland's prime minister &#124; World news &#124; The Observer |work=Guardian |location=UK |date= 16 May 2010|accessdate=18 June 2010 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2010/0610/Dutch-voters-boost-far-right-party-of-Geert-Wilders |title=Dutch voters boost far-right party of Geert Wilders |publisher=CSMonitor.com |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/newsbook/2010/06/dutch_elections?source=hptextfeature |title=The Dutch elections: Right turn |work=The Economist |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> The party has been regarded by some as [[Anti-Polish sentiment|anti-Polish]], [[Anti-Slavic sentiment|anti-Slavic]], [[Anti-Romanyism|anti-Romani]] and [[Islamophobia|anti-Muslim]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Immigration and Conflict in Europe |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=vTRzzVMzhScC |page=287 }} |page=287 |year=2010 |first=Rafaela M. |last=Dancygier |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}<br />{{Cite book |title=The challenge of pluralism: church and state in five democracies |year=2009 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |first1=Stephen V. |last1=Monsma |first2=J. Christopher |last2=Soper |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=LqtOyWU3D54C |page=68 }} |page=68}}<br />{{Cite journal |journal=Contemporary Sociology |first=Asef |last=Bayat |volume=36 |issue=6 |date=November 2007 |title=When Muslims and Modernity Meet}}</ref><ref name=\"radio\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/11/01/tea.party.europe.uk/index.html |publisher=CNN |title=UK far-right group boasts Tea Party links |first=Dan |last=Rivers |first2=Simon |last2=Hooper |date=2 November 2010}}<br />{{Cite news |agency=Agence France-Presse |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gn5AXQSKWbiyTMQ3hnbTnEBHn8SA |first=Mariette |last=Le Roux |date=10 June 2010 |title=Far-right election breakthrough shocks Netherlands}}</ref> [[Geert Wilders|Wilders]] however maintains that he is not anti-Muslim, only anti-Islam, summing up his views by stating \"I don't hate Muslims, I hate Islam\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/feb/17/netherlands.islam|title='I don't hate Muslims. I hate Islam,' says Holland's rising political star|last=Traynor|first=Ian|date=17 February 2008|accessdate=15 March 2009|work=The Guardian | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Positions==\n===Dual nationality===\nIn February 2007, PVV parliamentarian Fritsma introduced a motion that would have prohibited any parliamentarian or executive branch politician from having [[dual citizenship]]. The PVV claimed that dual nationals have unclear loyalty. The motion would have made it difficult, if not impossible for [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour]] MPs [[Ahmed Aboutaleb]] and [[Nebahat Albayrak]] to become members of the [[fourth Balkenende cabinet]]. The motion had to be withdrawn, however, after objection from the [[List of Speakers of the House of Representatives (Netherlands)|Speaker]] of the [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]], Gerdi Verbeet (Labour Party).<ref>{{cite news|title=MPs unimpressed with motion from PVV|url=http://www.expatica.com/nl/news/local_news/mps-unimpressed-with-motion-from-pvv-36615.html|publisher=Expatica|date=16 February 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> [[Maastricht University]] law professor [[:nl:Twan Tak|Twan Tak]] has commented on the risk in executive branch officials having dual citizenship.<ref>{{cite news|title='Smoren discussie dubbel paspoort schandalig'|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10112390/Nieuws/Politiek/Smoren-discussie-dubbel-paspoort-schandalig.htm|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=15 February 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152348/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10112390/Nieuws/Politiek/Smoren-discussie-dubbel-paspoort-schandalig.htm|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> however the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] as reviewed in 2010 ECtHR jurisprudence has reaffirmed that form of discrimination is a violation of a human right.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/pages/search.aspx?i=001-98428|title=HUDOC Search Page|work=coe.int}}</ref> However, in 2007 the PVV planned to call for a vote of no confidence against junior ministers Aboutaleb and Albayrak when the [[fourth Balkenende cabinet|new cabinet]] had its first meeting with the House of Representatives, claiming that their respectively Moroccan and Turkish passports put their loyalties into question.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutch politician doubts Muslim ministers' loyalty|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL242937120070224|agency=Reuters  |date=24 February 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> In the event, the motion was only supported by the PVV itself.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opposition criticises cabinet in debate|url=http://www.expatica.com/actual/article.asp?subchannel_id=19&story_id=37138|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929103132/http://www.expatica.com/actual/article.asp?subchannel_id=19&story_id=37138|archivedate=29 September 2007|publisher=Expatica|date=1 March 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe issue of dual nationality, however, was not over yet. On 2 March 2007, [[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]] reported that Labour Party MP [[Khadija Arib]], who had been sworn into parliament the day before, was sitting on a commission appointed by the [[Mohammed VI of Morocco|king of Morocco]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutch MP to serve as advisor to Moroccan king|url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/dut070302mc|publisher=[[Radio Netherlands]]|date=2 March 2007|author=el Ayoubi, Mohammed|author2=den Boer, Nicolien|accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref> The PVV said that this commission work endangers Arib's loyalty to the Netherlands, and that she should choose between being a member of the Dutch parliament or the Moroccan commission. Geert Wilders said that Arib's remark on national television that her loyalty lay neither with the Netherlands nor Morocco was shameful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kamer akkoord met Marokkaans advieswerk Arib|language=Dutch|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10115100/Nieuws/Politiek/Kamer-akkoord-met-Marokkaans-advieswerk-Arib.htm|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152355/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10115100/Nieuws/Politiek/Kamer-akkoord-met-Marokkaans-advieswerk-Arib.htm|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The liberal VVD party similarly remarked that her \"double orientation would hurt Dutch integration.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Kamp: Nevenfunctie Arib schaadt integratie|language=Dutch|url=http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1294450/Kamp:+Nevenfunctie+Arib+schaadt+integratie.html|publisher=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]]|work=[[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau|ANP]]|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526215256/http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1294450/Kamp:+Nevenfunctie+Arib+schaadt+integratie.html|archivedate=26 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All other parties were appalled by the PVV and VVD's comments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lange dag in de Kamer met veel hatelijkheden|language=Dutch|url=http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/article1777410.ece/Lange_dag_in_de_Kamer_met_veel_hatelijkheden|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120905102032/http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/article1777410.ece/Lange_dag_in_de_Kamer_met_veel_hatelijkheden|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 September 2012|newspaper=[[NRC Handelsblad]]|first=Derk|last=Stokmans|date=9 March 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nPerhaps in the light of the ''Moldova'' ruling, in the first Rutte government in 2010 chaired by the VVD leader, supported by the PVV, [[Marlies Veldhuijzen van Zanten]] became the new State Secretary for Health, Welfare and Sport, having both Dutch and [[Sweden|Swedish]] nationality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/Nieuws/Politiek/278676/Nieuwe-CDAstaatssecretaris-heeft-dubbele-nationaliteit.htm |title=Nieuwe CDA-staatssecretaris heeft dubbele nationaliteit |publisher=Elsevier.nl |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nThe party fielded a controversial motion in the 2007 ''[[prinsjesdag|general deliberations]]'' on the immigration budget, calling for a stop to immigration from Muslim countries. The [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]] at first declined to bring the motion forward for debate. Justice Minister [[Ernst Hirsch Ballin]] said it was in violation of the Dutch constitution and international law.<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister: Wilders' moslimmotie is onmogelijk|language=Dutch|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10147551/Nieuws/Politiek/Minister-Wilders-moslimmotie-is-onmogelijk.htm|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=22 November 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152402/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10147551/Nieuws/Politiek/Minister-Wilders-moslimmotie-is-onmogelijk.htm|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Another motion by the PVV, against police officers wearing [[veil]]s, did gain a parliamentary majority.<ref>{{cite news|title='Agente met hoofddoek absoluut onwenselijk'|language=Dutch|url=http://www.nu.nl/algemeen/1342274/agente-met-hoofddoek-absoluut-onwenselijk.html|publisher=[[NU.nl]]|date=4 December 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the PVV party launched a website named ''Reporting Centre on Central and East Europeans'' to receive complaints about Central and East European immigrants in the Netherlands. 'Do you have problems with people from Central and Eastern Europe? Have you lost your job to a Pole, a Bulgarian, a Romanian or another East European? We want to know,' the website states. It displays newspaper headlines such as 'Wouldn't it be better if you went back home?' and 'East Europeans, increasingly criminal'. The European Commission has condemned the website, and EU Justice Commissioner [[Viviane Reding]] declared, \"We call on all citizens of the Netherlands not to join in this intolerance. Citizens should instead clearly state on the PVV's website that Europe is a place of freedom.\"<ref>\"[http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2012/02/problems_with_poles_report_the.php Problems with Poles? Report them to us, says new PVV website]\". DutchNews.nl. 8 February 2012.</ref><ref>\"[https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE8191ML20120210 Dutch allow Wilders' anti-Pole website, EU critical]\". ''Reuters.'' 10 February 2012.</ref> The website caused a lot of controversy within the [[European Union]].<ref>\"[http://www.sofiaecho.com/2012/02/16/1767592_controversy-continues-over-wilders-anti-eastern-european-website Sofiaecho.com 16 February 2012]\". {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217125414/http://www.sofiaecho.com/2012/02/16/1767592_controversy-continues-over-wilders-anti-eastern-european-website |date=17 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Financing political parties===\nThe PVV has declared that, since it is against state subsidies, it rejects the idea of itself being financially supported by the government and believes the \"taxpayers should not pay for political parties they don't support\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/video/407199-zomergesprek-geert-wilders-pvv.html |title=Zomergesprek: Geert Wilders (PVV) - NOS Nieuws |publisher=Nos.nl |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Dutch Parliament discussed tightening the financial rules for political parties, forcing them to become more transparent. The PVV indicated that it would use any means available to avoid disclosing the identity of its donors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parool.nl/parool/nl/3587/POLITIEK-BINNENLAND/article/detail/3139689/2012/01/26/PVV-zoekt-mazen-in-wet-over-giften.dhtml |title=PVV zal alles doen om bekendmaking donateurs te vermijden - POLITIEK BINNENLAND - PAROOL |publisher=Parool.nl |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Party platform===\n{{Update-section|date=December 2017}}\n{{third-party|section|date=March 2012}}\nOther policies that Wilders mentions in his party programme for the [[2010 Dutch general election|2010 general election]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvv.nl/images/stories/Webversie_VerkiezingsProgrammaPVV.pdf|language=Dutch|title=De agenda van hoop en optimisme|publisher=Party for Freedom}}</ref>\n* Harsh punishment of [[Antisemitism|violence against Jews]] and the [[LGBT]] community, which it claims is disproportionately committed by Muslims (p.&nbsp;13)\n* Recording the ethnicity of all Dutch citizens. (p.&nbsp;11)\n* Prohibition of [[Dhabihah#Islamic slaughtering|halal]] and [[Shechita|kosher slaughter]] (p.&nbsp;55) (However, Wilders has stated that opposition to kosher slaughter was not part of his party's agenda and that support for the ban had been withdrawn)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora?id=282105|title=Diaspora &#124; Jewish diaspora &#124; The Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Limitation of [[Coffeeshop (Netherlands)|cannabis coffee shops]] within a radius of no less than 1 [[Kilometre|kilometer]] from schools (p.&nbsp;11)\n* Active repatriation of criminals of foreign citizenship and Dutch nationals originating from the [[Netherlands Antilles]] (p.&nbsp;11)\n* [[Deportation]] of criminals having foreign nationality or [[multiple citizenship]] back to their country of origin, after a prison sentence (p.&nbsp;13)\n* Restrictions on immigrant labour from new EU member states and Islamic countries (p.&nbsp;15)\n* Removal of resources from anti-climate change programs, development aid, and immigration services (p.&nbsp;17)\n* Abolition of the Dutch [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]] (p.&nbsp;19)\n* Shutting down of all Islamic schools (p.&nbsp;15)\n* Ban on [[Women in Islam|Islamic gender apartheid]] (p.&nbsp;15)\n* The General Pension (AOW) age not to be increased beyond 65 (p.&nbsp;21)\n* Governmental communication to be exclusively in Dutch or Frisian (p.&nbsp;35)\n* Dutch language proficiency and a 10-year Dutch residency and work experience requirement for welfare assistance (p.&nbsp;15)\n* Constitutional protection of the dominance of the Judeo-Christian and humanistic culture of the Netherlands (p.&nbsp;35)\n* Choosing to defend the essential elements of Dutch culture: freedom of the LGBT community, as well as assured equality of men and women which Islam may challenge (p.&nbsp;33)\n* Repeal of anti-smoking legislation in bars (p.&nbsp;39)\n* Investment in more nuclear power plants and clean coal plants to reduce dependency on imported oil and because coal is cheaper (p.&nbsp;47)\n* Withdrawal from the [[European Union]].\n* Return to the [[Dutch guilder|guilder]] (old Dutch currency) and abandonment of the [[euro]].\n* Abolition of the European Parliament and no cooperation in any EU activity.\n* Ask the EU to remove the \"Dutch\" star in the European flag.\n* Repeal flight tax or [[Carbon tax|carbon dioxide tax]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n* Binding referendum on subjects like the EU and a multicultural society.\n* No more tax money to (political) left organisations.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n* Keeping track of the ethnicity of people who have committed crimes.\n* Select policemen on \"decisiveness\".\n* Binding assimilation contracts for immigrants.\n* Taxes on the [[Hijab|Islamic headscarf]] and prohibition of the [[Quran|Koran]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n* Ban on headscarves in any public function.\n* Support [[Afrikaners]], as it is Dutch heritage.\n* Opposition to Turkey's membership in NATO; support for remaining in NATO.\n* Halt all support and propaganda for Palestine and Palestinians.\n* No more [[Wind turbine|windmills]] and funding for durability or CO2 reduction; no more \"fiscal greening\". {{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n== Name and symbols ==\nThe name 'Party for Freedom' (''Partij voor de Vrijheid'') is a reference to the [[Freedom Party (Netherlands)|Freedom Party]] (''Partij van de Vrijheid''), a Dutch political party founded in 1946, shortly after [[World War II]]. In 1948, the Freedom Party went on as the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]] (''Volkspartij voor Vrijheid en Democratie''), which is the party Wilders split from.<ref>{{cite news|title=Groep Wilders wordt Partij voor de Vrijheid|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/nieuws/politiek/artikel/asp/artnr/88062/index.html|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=23 February 2006|accessdate=5 April 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200935/http://www.elsevier.nl/nieuws/politiek/artikel/asp/artnr/88062/index.html|archivedate=30 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe party logo consists of the party name and a [[gull]] in red, white, and blue, which are the colors of the [[Flag of the Netherlands|Dutch flag]].<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"sargasso\">Willem Visser, \"[http://sargasso.nl/kleur-en-symboliek-nederlandse-politiek/ Kleur en symboliek in de Nederlandse politiek]\" (in Dutch), ''Sargasso.nl'', 2017. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref> The gull symbolises freedom or liberty.<ref name=\"sargasso\"/><ref name=\"historischnieuwsblad\">Bas Kromhout, \"[https://www.historischnieuwsblad.nl/nl/nieuws/10749/Wilders_gebruikt_%5c%e2%80%98besmet%5c%e2%80%99_logo.html Wilders gebruikt 'besmet' logo]\" (in Dutch), ''Historisch Nieuwsblad'', 2008. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref> The gull had also been used as a symbol by the [[National Socialist Movement in the Netherlands]] on propaganda posters and for their youth wing, but Wilders claimed it was not inspired by Nazi usage.<ref name=\"historischnieuwsblad\"/><ref>\"[http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/20624246/__Wilders_woedend_na_NSB-vergelijking__.html Wilders woedend over vergelijking met NSB]\" (in Dutch), ''[[De Telegraaf]]'', 2008. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\nIn order to register for elections in the Netherlands, a political party needs to be an [[Voluntary association|association]] ({{Lang-nl|vereniging}}), which can be founded by two or more members.<ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/onderwerpen/democratie/vraag-en-antwoord/hoe-richt-ik-een-politieke-partij-op Hoe richt ik een politieke partij op?]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]''. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.notaris.nl/een-vereniging-oprichten Hoe richt ik een vereniging op?]\" (in Dutch), ''Notaris.nl''. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref> The Vereniging Groep Wilders (Association Group Wilders) was founded by the [[natural person]] Geert Wilders and Stichting Groep Wilders ([[Foundation (nonprofit)|Foundation]] Group Wilders), of which Wilders is the only board member.<ref name=\"montesquieu\">Koen Vossen, \"[http://www.montesquieu-instituut.nl/id/vj5eflkxm6yg/een_unieke_partij_de_organisatie_van_de Een unieke partij. De organisatie van de PVV]\" (in Dutch), ''Montesquieu Instituut'', 2012. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref><ref>Paul Lucardie, \"[http://dnpp.ub.rug.nl/dnpp/pp/pvv/geschied PVV partijgeschiedenis]\" (in Dutch), ''[[University of Groningen]]'', 2013. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref> The association was later renamed to Partij voor de Vrijheid (Party for Freedom).<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/> After the creation of the association, Wilders disabled new member registration, resulting in his remaining the sole member of the party.<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"montesquieu\"/> The party does not organise public [[party conference]]s and does not have local departments, a [[youth wing]], or a [[Think tank|research institute]].<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"montesquieu\"/>\n\n==Financing==\nIn the Netherlands, a political party needs to have 1,000 members or more to be eligible for government funding, a requirement which the Party for Freedom does not meet with Wilders being the only member.<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"financinglaw\">\"[http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBR0033004/2016-01-01 Wet financiering politieke partijen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2016. Retrieved 9 March 2017.</ref>\n\nOn several instances the PVV applied for and received European Union funding.<ref>\"[http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2012/09/pvv_wrongly_claims_13000_from.php PVV wrongly claims \u20ac13,000 from Brussels for euro report: tv show]\", ''DutchNews.nl'', 2012.</ref>\n\nFinancially, the party has been largely relying on donations. The party has not disclosed any of its finances until 2013. According to [[Hero Brinkman]], a former MP for the party, the PVV received most of its finances from certain foreign (American) lobby-groups.<ref>\"[http://www.nu.nl/politiek/2768411/lobbykantoren-vs-steunen-pvv.html 'Lobbykantoren VS steunen PVV']\" (in Dutch), ''[[NU.nl]]'', 2012.</ref> According to [[Reuters]], [[Daniel Pipes|Daniel Pipes']] [[Middle East Forum]] paid for the trials and security of Geert Wilders and [[David Horowitz]] paid Wilders \"a good fee\" for two speeches given in the US.<ref>Anthony Deutsch & Mark Hosenball, \"[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/10/us-dutch-wilders-us-idUSBRE8890Q820120910 Exclusive: U.S. groups helped fund Dutch anti-Islam politician Wilders]\", ''[[Reuters]]'', 2012.</ref><ref>\"[http://vorige.nrc.nl/binnenland/article2544752.ece/Partners_Wilders_in_VS_verdienen_aan_acties_tegen_moslimextremisme Partners Wilders in VS verdienen aan acties tegen moslimextremisme]\" {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012085802/http://vorige.nrc.nl/binnenland/article2544752.ece/Partners_Wilders_in_VS_verdienen_aan_acties_tegen_moslimextremisme |date=12 October 2011 }} (in Dutch), ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 2010.</ref>\n\nSince 2013, Dutch political parties are required by law to disclose all donations of 4,500 euro or more.<ref name=\"financinglaw\"/><ref name=\"politicofinances\">Cynthia Kroet, \"[http://www.politico.eu/article/geert-wilders-far-right-party-suffers-donation-downturn/ Geert Wilders\u2019 far-right party suffers donation downturn]\", ''[[Politico Europe]]'', 2017. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref> The Party for Freedom disclosed no donations for 2013.<ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2014/10/01/pvv-financieel-verslag-over-2013 Financieel verslag PVV 2013]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2014. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref> For 2014 to 2016, the party disclosed a total of 148,391.07 euro in donations from the California-based [[David Horowitz Freedom Center]], a total of 18,700 euro in donations from a private donor in the Netherlands, and a donation of 6,853.70 euro from the New York-based company FOL Inc.<ref name=\"politicofinances\"/><ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2015/09/21/pvv---financieel-verslag-over-2014 Financieel verslag PVV 2014]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2015. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2016/10/13/financiele-verslagen-over-2015-van-politieke-partijen Financi\u00eble verslagen over 2015 van politieke partijen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2016. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2017/03/08/overzicht-giften-en-schulden-politieke-partijen-tweede-kamerverkiezingen Overzicht giften en schulden politieke partijen Tweede Kamerverkiezingen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2017. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref> The 2015 donations of just over 108,244 euro from the Freedom Center was \"the largest individual contribution to a Dutch political party that year.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/928684/the-dutch-far-rights-election-donors-are-almost-exclusively-american/|title=The Dutch far right\u2019s election donors are almost exclusively American|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|work=Quartz|access-date=11 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n===House of Representatives===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Election year\n! # of votes\n! % of overall vote\n!Rank\n! # of seats won\n! Change\n! Government \n|-\n! [[2006 Dutch general election|2006]]\n| 579,490<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\">\"[http://www.verkiezingsuitslagen.nl/Na1918/Verkiezingsuitslagen.aspx?VerkiezingsTypeId=1 Verkiezingsuitslagen Tweede Kamer 1918 - heden]\" (in Dutch), ''Kiesraad''. Retrieved 9 March 2017.</ref>\n| 5.89%<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n|#5\n| {{Composition bar|9|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| new\n| {{no2|In the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2010 Dutch general election|2010]]\n| 1,454,493<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n| 15.45%<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n|#3\n| {{Composition bar|24|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 15\n| {{Yes-No|In support of the [[First Rutte cabinet|VVD-CDA minority coalition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2012 Dutch general election|2012]]\n| 950,263<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n| 10.08%<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n|#3\n| {{Composition bar|15|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 9\n| {{no2|In the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2017 Dutch general election|2017]]\n| 1,372,941<ref name=\"generalelectionresults2017\">\"[https://www.kiesraad.nl/binaries/kiesraad/documenten/rapporten/2017/3/kerngegevens-tweede-kamerverkiezing-2017/kerngegevens-tweede-kamerverkiezing-2017/Kerngegevens